# Shell scripts must check out with LF even on Windows.
#
# With core.autocrlf=true and no rule here, a Windows clone rewrites every .sh
# to CRLF, and bash then reads the trailing \r as part of the last token on the
# line. The failures are quiet rather than loud:
#
#   build-agents.sh --check   reports AGENTS.md stale when it is byte-identical
#   install-skill.sh --list   finds no skills at all, and still exits 0
#
# Neither reproduces in CI, which runs on Linux and never sees a CRLF checkout.
*.sh text eol=lf

# Markdown is data for these scripts (skills are symlinked and read as-is), so
# keep it stable across platforms too.
*.md text eol=lf

# PowerShell is Windows-native; CRLF is correct there.
*.ps1 text eol=crlf
